\begin_layout Title
Case Study:
 The Economics of Shopping:
 Time,
 Money,
 and Retirement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Background
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This case study explores how an individual,
 Carol,
 allocates her time between leisure,
 work,
 and shopping.
 The focus is on understanding why Carol might consume more after retirement despite a potential reduction in total income.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Scenario
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Meet Carol,
 a woman in her late 50s who is contemplating how to allocate her time between work,
 leisure,
 and shopping as she approaches retirement.
 The time frame of the decision is one day (
\begin_inset Formula $24$
\end_inset

 hours).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Setting Up the Problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Given:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 = Consumption goods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 = Leisure time measured in hours.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 = Time spent on shopping measured in hours.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 = Time spent on work measured in hours.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 = Total available time in a day,
 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s+l+L=T$
\end_inset

 (typically 
\begin_inset Formula $T=24$
\end_inset

 hours).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 = Price of consumption goods,
 determined by 
\begin_inset Formula $p=f(s)$
\end_inset

,
 such that (its derivative) 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(s)<0$
\end_inset

 capturing the idea that as more time is spent shopping the better deals can the consumer obtain.
 We require that even if the consumer spends all the time shopping the price is positive (
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)>0$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 = Wage rate per hour.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 = Retirement income (converted to daily income).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
